{"id":"mai-bdli","kind":"ticket","type":"task","title":"Delphi synthesis: CRDT doc sync with Obsidian","tags":["research","delphi-synthesis"],"body":"# Delphi Synthesis: CRDT Doc Sync with Obsidian\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nFour independent oracles (two GPT-5.4 instances, two Claude Opus 4.6 instances) investigated the same bug from different angles. All four converged on an identical root cause with extremely high confidence: mergeViaCRDT() uses creationBody as the 3-way merge base on every sync, forever. After the first sync, this base becomes stale. Both peers then compute massive overlapping diffs from the ancient origin, and the CRDT faithfully preserves both as concurrent inserts, producing exponential duplication (2x, 4x, 8x per cycle).\n\nThe oracles diverged only on the preferred fix: GPT-5.4 oracles both recommend replacing the CRDT merge path with a plain snapshot-based 3-way text merge; Claude Opus oracles both recommend keeping the CRDT but feeding it the correct base via a properly implemented lastSyncBody(). This synthesis recommends the CRDT fix path — it is architecturally consistent with maitake's event-sourced model, is the smallest correct change, and keeps the CRDT available for genuine future concurrent editing. The 3-way text merge alternative would require the same lastSyncBody tracking infrastructure anyway.\n\nObsidian is not the root cause — it is a frequency amplifier. The bug reproduces with direct SyncDocs() calls and no UI at all. Any editor that repeatedly writes whole-file snapshots will trigger this path; Obsidian just fires it every ~2 seconds.\n\n## Convergent Findings\n\nAll four oracles confirmed independently — highest confidence.\n\nRoot cause: mergeViaCRDT() uses creationBody as merge base on every call.\nEvidence: pkg/notes/docs.go line ~549: base := creationBody\n\nlastSyncBody() is a dead stub — returns \"\", never called from mergeViaCRDT.\nEvidence: pkg/notes/docs.go line ~520: TODO comment + return \"\"\n\nThe yrs/y-crdt WASM layer is NOT buggy.\nEvidence: CRDT unit tests all pass; duplication is upstream of the library.\n\nThe bug reproduces without Obsidian or fsnotify.\nEvidence: Direct SyncDocs() calls produce 2-4-8-16-32 doubling of fragment counts.\n\nObsidian amplifies frequency, is not the root cause.\nEvidence: Reproduced with plain os.WriteFile full rewrites + SyncDocs().\n\nExponential growth confirmed empirically.\nEvidence: Oracle 1: body grew 25 -\u003e 46 -\u003e 90 -\u003e 179 -\u003e 352 -\u003e 694 chars in 6 rounds.\n\nCurrent test suite doesn't catch the regression.\nEvidence: Tests use one-shot merges or check Contains() not exact body.\n\nThe design gap is visible: the TODO names the fix.\nEvidence: lastSyncBody TODO comment: \"track last-sync body hash for better 3-way merge base\"\n\n## Divergent Findings\n\n### Key split: Fix path\n\nThe oracles diverged on whether to keep the CRDT or replace it.\n\nGPT-5.4 (Oracles 1 and 2) recommend: Replace CRDT with 3-way text merge.\nArgument: the file boundary is fundamentally snapshot-based; the editor gives maitake whole-file text, not CRDT operations. Once you're reconstructing operations from snapshots, a tracked-base 3-way text merge is the natural fit. Obsidian Sync itself uses diff-match-patch for markdown.\n\nClaude Opus (Oracles 3 and 4) recommend: Keep CRDT, fix the base.\nArgument: the CRDT layer is already built and working correctly. The fix is a 20-50 line change in Go — implement lastSyncBody() and use it as the merge base. The CRDT handles the hard concurrent-edit case that text merge can't (character-level interleaving when both agent and user edit simultaneously).\n\n### Why they diverged\n\nThis is not a contradiction about facts — both sides agree on root cause, mechanism, and required infrastructure (lastSyncBody tracking). The split is architectural philosophy: \"right tool for this boundary\" vs \"smallest correct change to existing design.\" Both approaches work; they share the same prerequisite.\n\n### Resolution\n\nThe two approaches converge on requirements and differ only on implementation medium:\n- Both need lastSyncBody stored per note\n- Both need it used as the merge base\n- Both need it updated after every successful sync\n\nThe CRDT fix is smaller, more consistent with the event-sourced model, and does not preclude future multi-peer collaborative editing.\n\n## Unique Discoveries\n\nOracle 1 (mai-kqnz): Discovered that SyncDocs emits two YDoc updates per sync — once from engine.Append(body) which calls updateYDoc, and again from the explicit ydoc event written by SyncDocs from the merge result. Secondary inconsistency to clean up.\n\nOracle 2 (mai-b955): Confirmed Obsidian Sync's own design uses diff-match-patch 3-way text merge for markdown (not CRDT), with a conflict-file fallback. Logseq, Foam, Dendron all use Git/file-level workflows at the markdown boundary.\n\nOracle 3 (mai-fczb): Key insight — \"The YDoc content AT LOAD TIME is effectively the last-sync base\" because the last sync set both note body and file to YDoc.Content(). This leads to the minimal ~20 line fix: use ydocContent as base instead of creationBody. Caveat: when BOTH note and file changed since last sync, ydocContent == state.Body (not last-synced body), so full lastSyncBody tracking is still needed for the concurrent case.\n\nOracle 4 (mai-q7me): Shadow sidecar approach (.maitake/shadows/\u003cnote-id\u003e). Important crash-safety insight: write the shadow BEFORE the doc file so if the process dies, the shadow is at worst fresher than the file (harmless).\n\nOracle 4 (mai-l4ec): Implementing lastSyncBody() as event-scan over field=\"lastsync\" events in the note's own event stream. Architecturally consistent with maitake's event-sourced model — no external sidecar files, fully reproducible from the note's event log.\n\n## Composite Answer: The Fix\n\nRecommended approach: Event-sourced lastsync + CRDT fix (~50 lines).\n\nThis synthesizes the key insights from Oracles 3 and 4 into one coherent design that is fully consistent with maitake's existing architecture.\n\n### Step 1: Implement lastSyncBody() via event scanning\n\nAfter each successful SyncDocs merge, append a lastsync event to the note:\n\n    engine.Append(AppendOptions{\n        TargetID: id,\n        Kind:     \"event\",\n        Field:    \"lastsync\",\n        Body:     mergedBody,\n    })\n\nUpdate lastSyncBody() to scan events (already in state.Events after fold):\n\n    func lastSyncBody(state *State) string {\n        for i := len(state.Events) - 1; i \u003e= 0; i-- {\n            if state.Events[i].Field == \"lastsync\" {\n                return state.Events[i].Body\n            }\n        }\n        return \"\" // no sync yet — caller falls back to creationBody\n    }\n\n### Step 2: Fix mergeViaCRDT() to use the last-sync base\n\nReplace the one line that sets base := creationBody with:\n\n    base := lastSyncBody(state)\n    if base == \"\" {\n        base = creationBody  // first sync — creation body is correct\n        if base == \"\" {\n            base = noteContent\n        }\n    }\n\nWith this change, each sync computes a SMALL diff from the last synchronized point. The CRDT sees small, non-overlapping concurrent inserts — exactly what it is designed to merge.\n\n### Step 3: Clean up the duplicate YDoc update\n\nRemove the redundant ydoc event emitted by SyncDocs after engine.Append(body) already called updateYDoc. Keep only one source of truth for YDoc state.\n\n### Why this approach wins\n\nRequires lastSyncBody tracking: Yes for both approaches.\nArchitecturally consistent with event-sourced model: YES for CRDT fix, No for 3-way text merge (would need external state or new paradigm).\nHandles concurrent character-level edits: Yes for CRDT fix, No for 3-way text merge (conflict markers).\nCode change size: ~50 lines for CRDT fix, ~100-150 lines for 3-way text merge.\nFixes the exponential duplication bug: Yes for both.\n\n### Alternative: If the team wants to remove WASM\n\nThe 3-way text merge path is valid. Replace mergeViaCRDT with a standard diff3 implementation using the same lastSyncBody infrastructure. Tradeoff: concurrent same-line edits produce conflict markers instead of clean interleaving. Acceptable if maitake's use case is primarily \"human edits in Obsidian, agent edits via mai\" with low simultaneous concurrency.\n\n## Testing Strategy\n\n### Category 1: Unit tests for merge logic (pure function)\n\n1. Regression: stale base causes duplication — Create note with body A, simulate N rounds of file-only edits (each round: full-file rewrite + SyncDocs). Assert fragment count stays 1, not 2/4/8/16. The critical test that would have caught the bug.\n2. File-only change — lastSync == note, file != note. Result must exactly equal file.\n3. Note-only change — lastSync == file, note != file. Result must exactly equal note.\n4. Non-overlapping concurrent edit — Note adds section A at bottom, file adds section B at bottom, from same base. Result must contain both A and B, each exactly once.\n5. Overlapping concurrent edit — Both sides change the same paragraph. Document behavior.\n6. Idempotence — Sync with no changes twice. Result unchanged.\n7. Large document (~2700 words), small edit — Result must be ~2700 words +/- change size. Not 5400+ words.\n8. Unicode/emoji/CJK — Multi-byte rune boundaries handled correctly.\n9. Empty note or empty file — Edge cases at boundary.\n10. First sync (no lastsync event) — Falls back to creationBody correctly.\n\n### Category 2: Integration tests simulating Obsidian behavior\n\n11. Repeated full-file saves (the regression test) — Create doc, materialize, then 10 rounds of full-file rewrite + SyncDocs. After each round: state.Body == fileContent. No size explosion.\n12. Obsidian-style append/edit sequence on large document — 2700-word doc, 5 edit cycles with small changes each. Final doc size \u003c 1.2x original.\n13. Agent edits + file edit, concurrent — Agent appends section (note body changes), file gets independent paragraph addition, sync. Both present exactly once.\n14. Restart persistence — Sync, recreate engine/process, sync again. lastsync event survives restart. No duplication on second sync.\n15. Frontmatter preserved through every cycle — YAML frontmatter unchanged across 10 sync rounds.\n\n### Category 3: Daemon / fsnotify tests\n\n16. Plain write events — Normal Obsidian-style write. Daemon picks up correctly.\n17. Atomic save (Remove + Create) — Already exists; keep. Verify no tombstone, no content loss.\n18. Autosave burst — 10 writes in 400ms. Debounce fires once. Final content correct.\n19. Edit after rm -rf docs/ and restore — Daemon recovers, no corruption.\n20. Repeated Obsidian saves after daemon restart — Daemon restart does not reset lastsync context.\n\n### Category 4: Adversarial / property tests\n\n21. 100 sync cycles, alternating note/file edits — Body size stays O(N), not O(2^N).\n22. Random edit sequences — Generate random (base, sequence of note/file edits), assert: after each sync note == file, no fragment appears more than natural occurrence count.\n23. Idempotence invariant — Syncing twice with no change is always a no-op.\n24. Convergence invariant — After any successful sync, note.Body == file.Content.\n25. Duplication detector — For any sequence of syncs, no substring of length \u003e 10 chars appears more times than expected from the source text.\n\n### Test repairs needed in current suite\n\n- Strengthen TestDocs_BothNoteAndFileChanged to assert exact expected merged body, not just Contains(marker).\n- Add exact-body assertions wherever tests currently only check substring presence.\n- Add TestSyncDocs_RepeatedFullFileSaves_DoNotDuplicateContent as a permanent regression test.\n\n## Confidence Assessment\n\nRoot cause is stale creationBody merge base: 98% — 4 independent reproductions, direct code trace.\nThe bug reproduces without Obsidian: 99% — Multiple oracles confirmed with direct SyncDocs calls.\nCRDT layer (yrs/y-crdt) is correct: 97% — CRDT unit tests pass; duplication mechanism understood.\nExponential doubling pattern (2^N): 96% — Oracle 1 measured exactly: 25-46-90-179-352-694 chars.\nlastSyncBody event-sourced fix is sufficient: 85% — Architectural analysis; not yet implemented and tested.\nCRDT merge is correct once base is fixed: 80% — Follows from CRDT semantics; needs integration test confirmation.\n\nUncertain areas:\n- Whether ydocContent == state.Body always holds (if updateYDoc has any code paths that miss a body change, the YDoc may lag). This assumption in Oracle 3's minimal fix needs verification.\n- Whether lastsync event body storage is acceptable for large documents (e.g., 50KB+ markdown). May need content-addressed deduplication.\n\n## Recommended Actions\n\n1. Write the regression test first (TestSyncDocs_RepeatedFullFileSaves_DoNotDuplicateContent) — confirm it fails with current code, confirm it passes after fix. This is the acceptance criterion.\n2. Implement lastSyncBody() by scanning note events for field=\"lastsync\" — event-scan in fold or inline in docs.go.\n3. Emit lastsync event after each successful SyncDocs merge — use engine.Append with kind=\"event\", field=\"lastsync\", body=mergedBody.\n4. Fix mergeViaCRDT() base selection — use lastSyncBody(state), fall back to creationBody if empty (first sync).\n5. Remove duplicate YDoc update — audit whether SyncDocs appends an extra ydoc event after engine.Append(body) already called updateYDoc. Remove the redundant one.\n6. Strengthen existing tests — add exact-body assertions to TestDocs_BothNoteAndFileChanged and similar tests that currently only check Contains.\n7. Add the full integration test suite — particularly the repeated-saves regression and large-document stability tests.\n\n## Appendix: Oracle Contributions\n\nOracle 1 (mai-kqnz) — GPT-5.4: Empirical reproduction showing exact 2^N doubling (25-\u003e694 chars in 6 rounds); discovered dual YDoc update emission bug.\n\nOracle 2a (mai-b955) — GPT-5.4: Confirmed Obsidian Sync itself uses diff-match-patch, not CRDT; added Logseq/Foam/Dendron external signal that snapshot-based approaches are standard.\n\nOracle 2b (mai-kjyq) — GPT-5.4: Confirmed base fix with two separate reproductions; clean 3-way merge design table with case-by-case breakdown.\n\nOracle 3a (mai-fczb) — Claude Opus 4.6: Key insight that YDoc content at load time IS the last-sync base; minimal ~20 line fix proposal using ydocContent.\n\nOracle 3b (mai-t1i8) — Claude Opus 4.6: \"Stale base snowball\" framing; per-cycle trace of the exact duplication mechanism; confirmed CRDT is correct tool if used correctly.\n\nOracle 4a (mai-q7me) — Claude Opus 4.6: Shadow sidecar design; crash-safety ordering (write shadow before doc file); YDoc compaction concern.\n\nOracle 4b (mai-l4ec) — Claude Opus 4.6: Event-sourced lastsync implementation via field=\"lastsync\" events; cleanest architectural fit with maitake's event model.","timestamp":"2026-04-03T12:29:33Z","branch":"main"}
